04999nam a22007935i 9780271087634DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710876347 a10.1515/97802710876342doi  a(DE-B1597)584267  a(OCoLC)1253313568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0900002bisacsh04a297.409662231 aOgunnaike, Oludamini, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeep Knowledge :bWays of Knowing in Sufism and Ifa, Two West African Intellectual Traditions /cOludamini Ogunnaike. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b4 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAfricana Religions ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: African Philosophy -- tPart 1: Ways of Knowing in Tijani Sufism -- t1 What Is Tijani Sufism -- t2 What Is Maʿrifa -- t3 How Is Maʿrifa Acquired -- t4 How Does Tarbiya Work -- tPart 2: Ways of Knowing in Ifa -- t5 What Is Ifa -- t6 Knowledge in Ifa -- t7 How Is Knowledge Acquired in Ifa -- t8 How Is Knowledge Verified in Ifa -- tPart 3: Comparing Ifa and Tijani Sufism -- t9 Comparing Ifa and Tijani Sufism -- t10 Comparative Conclusions -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is an in-depth, comparative study of two of the most popular and influential intellectual and spiritual traditions of West Africa: Tijani Sufism and Ifa. Employing a unique methodological approach that thinks with and from—rather than merely about—these traditions, Oludamini Ogunnaike argues that they contain sophisticated epistemologies that provide practitioners with a comprehensive worldview and a way of crafting a meaningful life.Using theories belonging to the traditions themselves as well as contemporary oral and textual sources, Ogunnaike examines how both Sufism and Ifa answer the questions of what knowledge is, how it is acquired, and how it is verified. Or, more simply: What do you know? How did you come to know it? How do you know that you know? After analyzing Ifa and Sufism separately and on their own terms, the book compares them to each other and to certain features of academic theories of knowledge. By analyzing Sufism from the perspective of Ifa, Ifa from the perspective of Sufism, and the contemporary academy from the perspective of both, this book invites scholars to inhabit these seemingly “foreign” intellectual traditions as valid and viable perspectives on knowledge, metaphysics, psychology, and ritual practice.Unprecedented and innovative, Deep Knowledge makes a significant contribution to cross-cultural philosophy, African philosophy, religious studies, and Islamic studies. Its singular approach advances our understanding of the philosophical bases underlying these two African traditions and lays the groundwork for future study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aIfa (Religion)zAfrica, West. 0aKnowledge, Theory of (Religion). 0aTijānīyahzAfrica, West. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Sufi.2bisacsh  aAfrican Islam.  aAfrican Philosophy.  aAfrican Traditional Religion.  aAfricana Philosophy.  aComparative Philosophy.  aIfa.  aIslam in Africa.  aSufism.  aTijaniyya.  aYoruba religion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271087634?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271087634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271087634/original  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL 